\section{Introduction}
%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%

\subsection{Background}

Neoclassical economic growth theory attributes output growth to growth rates of factors of production: capital stock and labor. In 1928, Amherst Professors Charles Cobb and Paul Douglas created the Cobb-Douglas production function that predicted manufacturing output ($y$) as a function of labor ($l$), capital stock ($k$), and a technological progress term ($\mathrm{e}^{(t-t_0)}$) \citep{Mishra:2007tv}

\begin{equation} \label{eq:CD}
  y_\mathrm{CD} = \mathrm{e}^{(t-t_0)} k^\alpha l^\beta,
\end{equation}

\noindent where

\begin{equation} \label{eq:y_def}
  y \equiv Y/Y_\mathrm{0},
\end{equation}

\begin{equation} \label{eq:k_def}
  k \equiv K/K_\mathrm{0},
\end{equation}

\noindent and

\begin{equation} \label{eq:l_def}
  l \equiv L/L_\mathrm{0};
\end{equation}

\noindent with $Y$ measured by GDP, $K$ measured in currency units, and $L$ measured in workers or work-hours.

In the Cobb-Douglas production function, capital and labor are related to output with an elasticity of unity, indicating constant returns to scale.

\begin{equation} \label{eq:CD_constant_returns_to_scale_constraint}
  \alpha + \beta = 1
\end{equation}

Using only labor and capital factors of production, neoclassical economic growth theory cannot predict the growth of the U.S. economy over the last 100 years.

%Figure 1 goes here

So, an exogenous "technological progress" term (\textit{A(t)}) is often included to better predict historical economic growth as a function of capital and labor factors of production. For the U.S., the \textit{A(t)} parameter is necessary: without it, the theory cannot accurately describe historical economic performance.

Neoclassical economic growth theory makes no attempt to understand the mechanisms by which technological progress affects economic growth, nor does it attempt to say how technological progress might vary from one economy to the next. Mathematically, technological progress is nothing more than a fitting parameter that aligns the predictions of equation 1 with historical data.

As shown in Equation 1 above, neoclassical economic theory neglects the role of energy input to the economy. However, (BASHMAKOV, 2007) and (MURPHY, 2011) indicate that the influence of energy on economic growth may far outweigh its cost share in the economy. That neoclassical economic growth theory ignores energy input is, therefore, cause for concern, and an inquiry into the proper approach to including energy as a factor of production in growth modeling is therefore, extremely relevant.

Many energy economists include energy as a factor of production (along with capital stock and labor) to improve predictions of historical economic growth. But, there is little agreement on how this should be done. Neither the mathematical form of the production function, nor which type of energy should be considered (thermal energy, exergy, of useful work) are consistent in the literature. Furthermore, there has been little empirical work done to assess the predictive ability of various energy-including production functions for different types of economies. This paper attempts to contribute to our understanding in these important areas.

\subsection{Mathematical Forms of the Production Function}
Many energy-including production functions have been used to predict economic growth. Three prominent functions are the Cobb-Douglas production function with an energy input as used by (AYRES AND WARR, 2008), the Stern Constant Elasticity of Substitution (CES) production function (STERN, 2010), and K\"{u}mmel's Linear Exponential (LINEX) production function (KUMMEL, 1980).

Similar to the Cobb-Douglas production function without an energy term, the Cobb-Douglas production function with energy (\textit{e}) includes constant returns to scale for the three factors of production.

\begin{equation}
  y_\mathrm{C-D} = A(t)k^\alpha l^\beta e^\gamma
\end{equation}

\begin{equation}
  e \equiv E/E_\mathrm{0}
\end{equation}

\begin{equation}
  \alpha + \beta + \gamma = 1
\end{equation}

(AYRES AND WARR, 2009) use this production function with useful work and exergy being the energy factors of production to descrive historic Japanese and American economies from 1900-2000. (FROLING, 2009) also uses a Cobb-Douglas production function with a thermal energy input to describe output for the global economy from 1800-1970. Fr\"{o}ling's Cobb-Douglas production function endogenizes labor with respect to fertility and mortality rates and separates the thermal energy factor of production into two types: biomass energy and coal energy. (SERRENHO, 2010) uses the Cobb-Douglas derivative with a thermal energy factor of production to describe output for the EU-15 countries. Serrenho divides the thermal energy factor into energy consumption from renewables, non-renewables, wastes, and imports.

Other energy economists use the Constant Elasticity of Substitution (CES) production function to describe economic growth with an energy factor of production. (VAN DER WERF, 2007) models various nested CES production functions for 12 OECD (Organisation for Economic Co-operating and Development) countries with respect to climate change policy. van der Werf concludes that (KL)E nesting structure (capital and labor combined, then energy added) best fits the historic data. (LECCA, 2011) also models a variety of CES production functions using a KLEM structure to determine how the energy factor of production's location affects results stability. (STERN, 2011) uses a CES production function that has a Cobb-Douglas production function embedded into the CES production function, following the (KL)E format. 

\begin{equation}
  y_\mathrm{CES} = \bigg{[} (1-\zeta)(A_\mathrm{L} l^\beta k^{1-\beta})^\phi + \zeta(A_\mathrm{E} e)^\phi \bigg{]} ^\frac{1}{\phi}
\end{equation}

\begin{equation}
  \phi = \frac{\sigma-1}{\sigma}
\end{equation}

Where $A_\mathrm{L}$ is the augmentation indice for labor and capital, $A_\mathrm{E}$ is the augmentation indice for energy, $\sigma$ is the elasticity of substitution between energy and value added aggregate, and $\zeta$ is the relative importance of labor/capital and energy. The elasticity of substitution between the capital and labor term and the energy term is less than unity, reflecting a minimum energy requirement for economic output. Stern applies his CES function to the Swedish economy from 1800-2000, which reflects the significance in the transfer from wood to more energy-intensive fossil fuel sources in promoting economic growth.

The final production function chosen for our comparison was the (KUMMEL, 1980, 1985, 2002) LINEX production function.

\begin{equation}
  y_\mathrm{LINEX} = e \textrm{exp} \bigg{[} a_\mathrm{0} \bigg{(} 2-\frac{l+e}{k} \bigg{)} + a_\mathrm{0} c_\mathrm{t} \bigg{(} \frac{l}{e} - 1 \bigg{)} \bigg{]}
\end{equation}

\begin{equation}
  a = a_\mathrm{0} \frac{l + e}{k}
\end{equation}

\begin{equation}
  \beta = a_\mathrm{0} \bigg{(} c_\mathrm{t} \frac{l}{e} - \frac{l}{k} \bigg{)}
\end{equation}

\begin{equation}
  \gamma = 1 - \frac{a_\mathrm{0} e}{k} - a_\mathrm{0} c_\mathrm{t} \frac{l}{e}
\end{equation}

Where $a_\mathrm{0}$ is a parameter representing capital efficiency and $c_\mathrm{t}$ is a parameter representing energy demand. (KUMMEL, 1980) inserted an energy factor of production into the Cobb-Douglas derivative, then assumed constant elasticity for the energy, labor, and capital factors of production. (KUMMEL, 1985) then partially integrated the Cobb-Douglas derivative to form the LINEX production function. K\"{u}mmel uses his LINEX production function to describe economic output for the economies of the U.S., Japan, and Germany (KUMMEL, 2002). (AYRES AND WARR, 2010) compare the LINEX production function with the Cobb-Douglas production function to assess economic growth for Austria, the United Kingdom, the United States, and Japan. 

\subsection{Quantification of Energy}
The literature shows three types of energy used in production functions: thermal energy, exergy, and useful work. Thermal energy ($e$) is the heat content of an energy carrier. Exergy ($x$) is the maximum useful work that can be extracted from an energy carrier by a process that brings the system into equilibrium with a heat reservoir (typically the surrounding environment). Useful work ($u$) includes the direct energy that goes into an economy, including work from machines, human muscles, and animals. Most energy economists have used thermal energy for the energy factor of production in the production function, including (STERN, 2011), (FROLING, 2009), (SERRENHO, 2010), and (KUMMEL, 1980, 1985, 2002). (AYRES AND WARR, 2009) introduced the idea of using exergy and useful work in a production function in order to include the importance of efficiency gains in energy production over the last century. Little work has been done comparing the predictive ability of each type of energy quantification in production functions.

%Figure 2 goes here.

(ADD FIG REF) exemplifies the importance of the quantification of energy's effect on growth modeling. The indexed values of $e$, $x$, and $u$ have very different growth rates. In particular, $u$ grows faster than either $e$ or $x$ due to efficiency gains in economies. The quantification of energy as $u$ suggests that perhaps technological progress $A(t)$ is a proxy for increasing energy efficiency in the U.S. economy. 

\subsection{Economy Types}

In most economic growth literature, economists assess developed economies primarily from North America or Europe. Examples of developed economies being assessed include (KUMMEL, 1980) applying LINEX to describe the West German economy, (SERRENHO, 2010) applying Cobb-Douglas variants to EU-15 countries, (VAN DER WERF, 2007) applying CES nesting variants to the 12 OECD countries, (LECCA, 2011) applying CES nesting variants to the Scottish economy, (STERN, 2011) applying CES to describe the Swedish economy, and (AYRES AND WARR, 2010) using LINEX and Cobb-Douglas to describe the Austrian, American, British, and Japanese economies. There is a need to evaluate economies at all stages of growth.

